      <div class="msgContentFrame">Whole lotta stupid in this thread. <br /> <br />1. Torrents cannot be modified, there are checks and balances built into the process to prevent it.  Now if you're downloading your torrent file from elseware, well, that's just dumb. <br />2. A token does protect your account, you cannot bypass a token remotely. <br />3. The idea that a &quot;real hacker&quot; can get into your token protected account is laughable. <br /> <br />A token protected account is nearly invulnerable.  There are a couple of ways that it could be bypassed, all of which would require access to your system.  They would probably have to hijack your connection after you entered your token generated pass code which isn't an easy task, would only give them one time access, and would be BLATANTLY obvious to the user. <br /> <br />Non-token accounts are much easier.  Bad/no virus protection, crappy websites, phishing sites, no firefox/noscript.  Contrary to popular belief, most viruses do not come from torrents.  In fact, very few do and any resident virus scanner will catch them before they touch your system. <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Nov 19th 2010  5:01pm by Yodabunny </span></i></div>
      <div class="msgFtFrame">
        <div class="msgFtFrameFix"></div>
